My Review: Murata, you are one weird woman. But your weird writing is coveted

Title: Tomorrow, and Tomorrow, and Tomorrow
Author: Gabrielle Zevin
My Review:
‘How do you see it?’

Amazing.

I think I may be the perfect target audience for this book - someone who has grew up, and partially been brought up, with games. Games to escape, games to celebrate, games to compete, games to play. I also work as a programmer - the infinite gaming and technology references weren’t lost on me, and definitely made me smile (and even exhale sharply from my nose) whilst reading. I also coincidentally had a broken foot whilst reading this (as does one of this books main characters, Sam, which helped to make him even more relatable)

Tomorrow, and tomorrow, and tomorrow is a love story that isn’t a love story. It’s brutally real and raw. Life isn’t perfect - we don’t live in a made up, idealistic video game world - and Zevin fully explores that, taking us through the high highs and the low lows that reality forces us to embrace and endure.

This book is truly special, and will be one I will cherish fondly

5/5

Title: Earthlings
Author: Sayaka Murata
My Review:
Earthlings was rather difficult to read, but at the same time difficult to put down. It covered (uncomfortably) sensitive topics like sexual and emotional abuse, and is definitely not what I was expecting solely from the cover and blurb.

It’s difficulty to rate this because although I didn’t enjoy reading it, I didn’t want to stop reading it - it held my attention greatly but made me feel really uncomfortable throughout - though I imagine this was Murata’s intention.

3/5

Title: Circe
Author: Madeline Miller
My Review:
Sadly, this book sent me into a reading slump. I was really excited after thoroughly adoring Song of Achilles by the same author.

The book was beautifully written, with memorable, gorgeous quotes such as ‘No wonder I have been so slow, I thought. All this while I have been a weaver without wool, a ship without the sea. Yet now look where I sail.’ and ‘But in a solitary life, there are rare moments when another soul dips near yours, as stars once a year brush the earth. Such a constellation was he to me.’

However, there was (to me) no clear direction which the book was taking. Perhaps I just prefer plot focused books, as this was obviously very much about building the Circe character and the hardships she went through to make her the person she is at the end of the book. I wasn’t looking forward to picking the book up, and wasn’t overly interested in seeing the next hardship she would face.

However, the beautiful writing made up for this, hence the 3 star review. I do look forward to Millers ‘Persephone’ and hope it’ll be more like SoA!

Title: If on a Winter's Night a Traveller
Author: Italo Calvino

Title: The Dangers of Smoking in Bed: Stories
Author: Mariana Enríquez
My Review:
This book is a short story collection - It’s hard to give the collection a genre, but each story is weird and wonderful and haunting, yet captivating, leaving you wanting more whilst also questioning what it is you want more of

After reading, each story feels like a midday slumbers fever dream - although you get a full plot, you yearn for more than a glimpse into the universe which Enriquez builds (rather quickly)

Some stories are extremely strange, but it’s worth pushing through and allowing yourself to be weirded out, to be uncomfortable - the fact that words on a page can make you feel so disgusted says a lot about Enriquez’ writing

Title: On Earth We’re Briefly Gorgeous
Author: Ocean Vuong
My Review:
On Earth We're Briefly Gorgeous is somewhat autological - for it in itself is briefly gorgeous.

The book explores the life of a Vietnamese boy growing up in America, through the medium of letters to his mother - who is illiterate. It details how the boy - 'Little Dog' ventured his way through this life, the hardships which he endured, and how they affected him. This includes the lasting effect of war, abuse, homosexuality, and love.

Vuong has previously successfully published poetry, and that evidently manifests through his writing in this novel - the prose is most certainly the most beautiful I have ever read. The writing is largely metaphorical, and is open to interpretation.

Although indeed brief, this book is an emotional, important and truly gorgeous novel

4.5/5

Title: The Secret History
Author: Donna Tartt
My Review:
This is my new favourite book - which in itself is a title I don't think I've ever distinctly appointed. I hope this portrays the love which I have for The Secret History.

Everything - truly everything, from the setting, the romanticised academia, the way Tartt makes me love very hateable characters, the way I root for the villain, the immoral - though I still don't fully understand why.

If you want a beautifully written, engaging, absorbing book - this is it. I usually enjoy a mystery, or enjoy the slow unravel of a plot - but we are told on the first page of the death of Bunny, and exactly who killed him, this stealing my usual reasons for enjoying a book. Yet I would describe the experience I had reading this as none other than perfection.

I truly can't put into words how much I thoroughly adored TSH, and will likely be re-reading it soon. The perfect read as the leaves begin to fall and the days begin to darken.

5/5.

Title: Little Fires Everywhere
Author: Celeste Ng
My Review:
I really loved this book! As a young(ish) male, it made me consider things I haven't before, such as what it means to be a mother, and how people can show love.

It made me think about how people have different paths in life, and that living fully can be very different for different people. It was also the first book to make me really cry.

4.5/5

Title: Before the Coffee Gets Cold (Before the Coffee Gets Cold, #1)
Author: Toshikazu Kawaguchi
My Review: Although this was a quick read, you definitely have time to emotionally connect with the characters of the book, and the stories contained within are all thought provoking and cover potentially sensitive/difficult issues. A book that really makes you think about discovering the truth behind the 'what ifs' that linger in the back of your mind.
